Give your Openclaw the Memory it Needs (Full Guide)

This guide covers the three common ways memory fails, the configuration changes that fix most issues, and the advanced tools (QMD, Mem0, Cognee, Obsidian) that make memory production-grade.

## The Three Common Memory Failures

### Failure Mode 1: Memory Is Never Saved
Agent decides what to save — important context slips through because the model deemed it not worth storing.

### Failure Mode 2: Memory Is Saved But Never Retrieved
Even when facts make it to disk, the agent answers from context window instead of searching memory.

### Failure Mode 3: Context Compaction Destroys Knowledge
Older messages get summarized or removed to avoid token limits. Info only in active conversation is destroyed. Even MEMORY.md content loaded at session start can get summarized away.

## Basic Fixes

### 1. Enable Memory Flush (Critical)
Triggers a silent turn before compaction that prompts agent to write durable memories to disk.

```json
{
  "compaction": {
    "memoryFlush": {
      "enabled": true,
      "softThresholdTokens": 40000,
      "prompt": "Distill this session to memory/YYYY-MM-DD.md. Focus on decisions, state changes, lessons, blockers. If nothing: NO_FLUSH",
      "systemPrompt": "Extract only what is worth remembering. No fluff."
    }
  }
}
```

Key: customize the prompt, raise softThresholdTokens to 40000 to trigger flushes earlier.

### 2. Configure Context Pruning
```json
{
  "contextPruning": {
    "mode": "cache-ttl",
    "ttl": "6h",
    "keepLastAssistants": 3
  }
}
```

### 3. Enable Hybrid Search
```json
{
  "memorySearch": {
    "enabled": true,
    "sources": ["memory", "sessions"],
    "query": {
      "hybrid": {
        "enabled": true,
        "vectorWeight": 0.7,
        "textWeight": 0.3
      }
    }
  }
}
```

BM25 catches exact matches (error codes, project names) that vector search misses.

### 4. Index Past Sessions
```json
{
  "memorySearch": {
    "sources": ["memory", "sessions"]
  },
  "experimental": {
    "sessionMemory": true
  }
}
```

## Advanced Memory Solutions

### QMD (by @tobi, CEO of Shopify)
- Opt-in replacement for built-in SQLite indexer
- Local sidecar: BM25 + vectors + reranking
- Can index external document collections (Obsidian vault, project docs, Notion exports)

### Mem0 (YC-backed)
- Stores memories outside context window — compaction cannot destroy them
- Auto-Capture: detects and stores info without depending on LLM judgment
- Auto-Recall: searches and injects relevant memories before agent responds
- Solves Failure Modes 1 and 3 completely
- Installs as OpenClaw plug-in

### Cognee: Knowledge Graphs
- Builds knowledge graph from data
- Queries relationships between entities
- Good for enterprise/multi-agent teams
- Requires Docker

### Obsidian Integration
Option 1: Symlink memory folder
```bash
ln -s ~/workspace/memory ~/Obsidian/AgentMemory
```

Option 2: Index vault via QMD (recommended)
- Everything in Obsidian becomes searchable by agents
- Obsidian 1.12 CLI allows metadata queries (cheaper than reading full files)

## Multi-Agent Memory Architecture

Layer 1: Private memory per agent (own workspace, MEMORY.md, daily notes)
Layer 2: Shared reference files (_shared/ directory — user profile, agent roster, conventions)
Layer 3: QMD with shared paths (agents search same reference docs, private memory stays private)
Layer 4: Coordination ("Chief of Staff" agent reads core files at session start, maintains consistency)

## Key Takeaway
Stop expecting memory to be automatic — it isn't. Configure it explicitly.